  &lt;figcaption&gt;
    Johns Hopkins University COVID-19 dashboard
  &lt;/figcaption&gt;


&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What struck me about these dashboards is that although they provide comprehensive reports on the
absolute number of cases identified &amp;ndash; some even provide in-depth information on individual cases(!) &amp;ndash;
they lack a population-wide context.  In particular, I found myself wondering what these numbers
meant in terms of the fraction of (per-country) populations affected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;approach&#34;&gt;Approach&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I reasoned that perhaps a more interpretable picture of the scale and development of the situation
could be provided by normalizing the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases per country with per-country population estimates.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Luckily the folks at JHU have freely made available their meticulously curated datasets through a

&lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;GitHub repository&lt;/a&gt;, which they continue to update on a daily basis.
In addition, the World Bank provides 
&lt;a href=&#34;https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.POP.TOTL&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;population count estimates&lt;/a&gt;
for over 250 countries world-wide.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Combined&lt;sup id=&#34;fnref:2&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:2&#34; class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; role=&#34;doc-noteref&#34;&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;, these datasets open up an alternative view of the COVID-19 situation,
in terms of the percentage of per-country populations (confirmed to be) affected by the virus.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;alert alert-warning&#34;&gt;
  &lt;div&gt;
    &lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER&lt;/strong&gt;: I am not a virologist or epidemiologist &amp;ndash; I realize there are &lt;em&gt;many&lt;/em&gt; caveats to interpreting these data, most of which I am not addressing here.
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;results&#34;&gt;Results&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;!--
### Interpretation
Different countries, and their governments and infrastructures, have wide ranging approaches for 
dealing with the COVID-19 situation.
As such, although viruses know no (country) boundaries, we expect to see different patterns of 
viral infection progression and containment between countries.
